Let’s understand chunk overlap very simply with a clear example.

What is Chunk Overlap?

Chunk overlap = Some part of the previous chunk is repeated in the next chunk to preserve context.

Think like this:

Instead of cutting text like this:

Chunk 1 → 0 to 100 characters
Chunk 2 → 101 to 200 characters

We do this:

Chunk 1 → 0 to 100
Chunk 2 → 80 to 180

Here 80–100 is repeated.

That repeated part is called chunk overlap.

⸻

Simple Real Example

Suppose text is:

Virat Kohli is one of the best batsmen in the world. He plays for RCB in IPL.

Without overlap (chunk_size=40, overlap=0)

Chunk 1:
Virat Kohli is one of the best batsmen

Chunk 2:
in the world. He plays for RCB in IPL

Problem:
Meaning split.

If user asks:
Which team does Virat Kohli play for?

Chunk1 → has Virat
Chunk2 → has RCB

Retriever may fail.

⸻

With overlap (chunk_size=40, overlap=10)

Chunk 1:
Virat Kohli is one of the best batsmen

Chunk 2:
best batsmen in the world. He plays for RCB

Notice:
“best batsmen” repeated.

Now context connected.

⸻

Why chunk overlap exists (real reason)

When splitting, sometimes:
	•	Sentence breaks
	•	Idea breaks
	•	Context breaks

Overlap ensures:
Next chunk still knows previous context.

⸻

Visual Understanding

Without overlap:

[Chunk1] [Chunk2]

With overlap:

[Chunk1]
        [Chunk2]

The middle part overlaps.

⸻

Engineering Definition

If:

chunk_size = 100
chunk_overlap = 20

Then:

Chunk1:

0–100

Chunk2:

80–180

Chunk3:

160–260

Formula idea:

Next chunk start =
previous_end − overlap

⸻

One line understanding ⭐

Chunk overlap repeats some text between chunks so meaning is not lost.

⸻

How much overlap should we use?

General rule:

10–20% of chunk size

Example:

Chunk Size	Overlap
100	10–20
500	50–100
1000	100–200


⸻

One practical intuition (very important)

Think like reading a book:

If I tear pages exactly:
You may miss story connection.

If I repeat last few lines:
You understand next page better.

Chunk overlap = repeating last few lines.

